<DOC><DOCNO> AP890725-0240 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0159EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-25 0830</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0870</SECOND><DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Paramount Communications Inc. abandonedits $12.2 billion hostile bid for Time Inc. after the DelawareSupreme Court upheld a lower court decision allowing Time toproceed with its $14 billion buyout of Warner Communications Inc.   The three-judge panel unanimously sustained on Monday a rulingby Judge William T. Allen, affirming the rights of corporatedirectors to decide the future course of their companies.   The decision ended Paramount's seven-week bid to acquire Time.Paramount issued a statement that it was dropping its $200 a sharebuyout offer.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Time Inc. and Warner Communications Inc., havingdefeated Paramount Communications Inc.'s challenge to theirproposed merger, proceeded with their plan to create Time WarnerInc., the world's largest communications concern.   Time and Warner, which originally planned to merge in a stockswap transaction, revised the deal to provide instead for Time toacquire Warner in a $14 billion, or $70 a share, tender offer.   After the offer expired at 5 p.m. Monday, Time said it held morethan 117 million of Warner's 200 million common shares outstanding.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Bush administration hailed the new Mexicandebt-reduction package as a breakthrough for its Third World debtstrategy, but others were decidedly less enthusiastic.   Several members of Congress and private bankers said Monday theybelieved the final agreement with Mexico offered a glimmer of hopefor the debt-strapped Third World, but they said the success of theplan hinged on how far commercial banks would ultimately be willingto go.</TEXT><DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Honeywell Inc. made itself less attractive tocorporate raiders by saying it will cut 4,000 jobs, retreat fromits $1.4 billion weapons business and provide added cash toshareholders.   The sweeping restructuring announced Monday will include thesale of a ``substantial portion'' of the company's 50 percent stakein Yamatake-Honeywell, a Japanese controls maker. Analysts havevalued the holding at nearly $1 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government posted a $7.79 billion budgetsurplus in June, smaller than a year ago, but the deficit for thefirst nine months is mounting at a slower rate than 1988.   The government said Monday that the June surplus, a normal breakin a string of monthly deficits because corporations andindividuals make quarterly tax payments in the month, followed a$25.47 billion deficit in May.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ferruzzi Group called for a study of ChicagoBoard of Trade operations, in a followup of the soybean processor'scriticism of the exchange's emergency order that required tradersto reduce their holdings in soybean futures contracts.   David H. Swanson, president of Central Soya Co. and a member ofFerruzzi's executive committee, said Monday the emergency orderillustrated that the exchange had failed to keep up with the globalexpansion of commodities trading.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Cleanup costs stemming from its disastrousAlaskan oil spill helped caused Exxon Corp.'s second quarter profitto plummet by more than $1 billion, the nation's biggest oilcompany reported.   Exxon said Monday its net income fell 87 percent to $160million, or 13 cents a share, from $1.2 billion, or 90 cents ashare, in the comparable 1988 quarter.   Exxon said a special provision in the second quarter forexpenses and insurance claims stemming from the March 24 spill inAlaska's Prince William Sound reduced its net income by $850million, or 67 cents a share.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Justice Department said it supported atenfold increase to $10 million in the maximum fine for criminalantitrust violations by corporations.   The department, noting it is conducting more than 150 grand juryinvestigations of alleged criminal antitrust violations, said anincrease was needed to deter price fixing, bid rigging and unlawfulattempts by corporations to control the market on certain products.   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said Monday that he supportedlegislation pending in Congress that would increase the maximumfine from $1 million to $10 million for corporate antitrustviolations. </TEXT><DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The investment group proposing to buyNorthwest Airlines' parent company for $3.65 billion said it was onthe brink of closing the deal.   More than 99 percent of shares in NWA Inc. had been tendered tothe group, Wings Holdings Inc. by Monday morning, according to thegroup headed by Alfred Checchi, the former Marriott Corp. treasurer.   Checchi said his financing was nearly in place and he waspressing for early termination of the waiting period required underthe Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust Improvement Act.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market moved broadly lower in light activity Monday,as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials lost 22.38 to 2,584.98$   The dollar slipped against major European currencies, but edgedup against the Japanese yen.   Bond prices edged higher in quiet dealings.   Energy futures prices declined sharply; copper prices climbed;grain and soybean futures fell; livestock and pork prices finishedmixed and precious metals were up slightly.</TEXT></DOC>